          <div class="section-heading">
            <p class="eyebrow">Why exterior drains matter</p>
            <h2>What happens when exterior drains are neglected</h2>
            <p>Exterior drains face conditions interior drains never see — leaves in the fall, freeze-thaw cycles in winter, storm runoff in spring, and root growth year-round. They are also the drains most likely to be forgotten until damage appears.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="trust-stack">
            <article><span>01</span><div><h3>Foundation water damage</h3><p>Clogged exterior drains allow storm water to pool against the foundation, seeping through cracks and causing basement flooding, efflorescence, and structural damage over time.</p></div></article>
            <article><span>02</span><div><h3>Driveway and garage flooding</h3><p>Blocked driveway drains and trench drains let water pool on the driveway surface, flood the garage, and damage vehicles, tools, and stored belongings.</p></div></article>
            <article><span>03</span><div><h3>Landscape erosion</h3><p>When drainage systems fail, water follows the path of least resistance — washing away mulch, eroding soil, undermining retaining walls, and destroying plantings.</p></div></article>
            <article><span>04</span><div><h3>Ice hazards in winter</h3><p>Standing water from clogged drains freezes on walkways, driveways, and patios, creating dangerous slip-and-fall hazards throughout the winter months.</p></div></article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section section--muted">
        <div class="container split">
          <div>
            <p class="eyebrow">Warning signs</p>
            <h2>Signs your exterior drains need attention</h2>
            <p>Watch for these indicators that your outdoor drainage system needs professional cleaning or repair.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="callout-list">
            <div><strong>Puddles on the driveway after light rain</strong><span>Driveway drain basins or outlet lines are restricted and cannot handle normal rainfall volume.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Water pooling against the garage door or foundation</strong><span>Drains are overwhelmed or completely blocked, directing water toward the structure instead of away from it.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Soggy yard near downspouts</strong><span>Downspout extensions or underground connections are blocked, dumping roof runoff directly against the foundation.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Basement seepage in the same spot every storm</strong><span>Exterior drainage is missing, failed, or clogged in the area directly above the interior leak.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Mulch or soil washing across the lawn</strong><span>The drainage path is overwhelmed and water is finding its own route, carrying landscaping material with it.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Pop-up emitters that no longer open</strong><span>Outlet lines are blocked with debris or damaged by roots, preventing the system from discharging.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

